title: Has anybody beaten Eminem in rap yet? - Quora

response.answer_text: Top R&B/Hip-Hop Artists - Year-End 2017 As of 2017, 34 artists have beaten Eminem in rap. Eminem placed as the 35th best selling hip hop/R&B artist in the country. That means there are 34 people who have beaten him, by being more popular and better selling. Obviously that’s not what you meant, but to be completely honest I’m not sure what you did mean. Are you referring strictly to rap battles and beefs? If so not really, in that no rap beef has caused his career to derail. He did that himself. Are you referring to skill level in terms of flow and rhyme schemes? That’s a bit more complex and less concrete, but I’d say guys like Busta Rhymes and Techn9ne had him beat long ago. But again, that’s pretty vague. At the moment, he is probably the most notable rapper who commonly uses that style. Are you referring to quality of music? I’d say he hasn’t been that good in overall quality for a long time. How long that time is a question for another day, as I’m not actually sure of my own opinion on that. I don’t think he’s bad though. Sure, he’s made a few monstrosities starting with re-, but Kamikaze did win me over in the end. But he is definitely not the best current rapper. If I had to pick, I’d give that crown to Kendrick, but I’m not certain. There’s a lot of great talent and high quality music being made in the genre right now. But I’m getting off topic. Let’s bring it back to the question: has Eminem been beaten? There’s really only one reliable way to measure it that isn’t up to opinion, and that’s pure numbers. Eminem is very much a relic of a previous generation at this point. Some people respect him for his contributions to the culture, but his recent attacks on the state of hip hop have turned many people away from him. The single worst thing about Kamikaze is the fact that it exists. No relevant rapper or artist of any genre makes an entire full-length album attacking people for criticizing his previous album, especially not if that previous album is as godawful as the one in question. I like Kamikaze but goddamn is that hard to get over. This several months will be a goldmine for future historians studying his career. Look, Eminem is fading. Sure, Kamikaze debuted at #1 and spawned several hit singles that probably won’t drop off the charts nearly as quickly as the ones from Revival, but he’s still fading. On one hand, I’d love to see him return to form. But on the other, there is a point where you need to just leave things as they are. He had the perfect opportunity to back in 2013, after he dropped the Marshall Mathers LP2. That is his best album since 2002, and would have been a perfect way to end his career. Sure, he’d still have some truly awful music to his name, but he’d have ended on a high note. Instead we got Revival, which is just sad on every level. It’s a terrible work of music, but also it’s painful to see someone so talented fade away so clearly. In the end the only person that beat Eminem was himself. Sure, others overtook him in quality and relevance, but he put himself in the position that allowed them to do that.

That all depends on your definition of ‘beaten’ Do you mean in sales? Then yes, OutKast have him beat for the bestselling rap album of all time. Do you mean in critical acclaim? By that line of thinking, Dr Dre has a better average when it comes to critical reception on his albums. But let’s look at rap beef. Not a single person has beaten Eminem in a rap beef. The only person to ever beef with him that’s even come close to being his lyrical equal is Canibus. And he beat Canibus. What about on a track? Eminem literally created a term used to describe when a rapper got murdered on their own track. And since then, he’s Renegaded dozens of rappers in guest spots. But I’ll admit, there’s been times when somebody has gotten the better of him. Royce da 5’9” has been his lyrical superior on some tracks, including a good chunk of Hell: The Sequel. SPIN Magazine called Sticky Fingaz’s guest verse on Remember Me “the only time a rapper gets the better of Eminem on the Mathers LP” I can’t think of anyone else who’s gotten the better of Eminem on a track. I guess he wasn’t the best on Speedom. So, to answer your question, it depends on how you judge beating someone. But in most cat categories, Eminem reigns supreme.

I admire your persistence Mario… your not willing to trust in just one persons opinion. Let’s be truthful; it’s really a matter of semantics right? I will cut to the chase; I assume you mean in a “beef”. Canibus came close, but after some time went by nobody cared. If you mean freestylin then yes at the rap olympics by a rapper named Juice; who was really blown away by Marshall Mathers. Now to be completely fair, Em was homeless, had nothing to go home to in Detroit; Kim & Hailie moved, Em had never freestyled to something at such a grand scale like the Rap olympics, and had all of 40 bucks in his pocket to his name (talk about pressure). Some of the “rumors” I have read and heard about Juice were admittedly; that he came in halfway through the olympics “fresh” to battle. Juice worked at the Record store that was sponsoring the Rap olympics. Juice hid behind a camera monitor so Em didn’t know who he was battling until a little later? Either way Marshall took an “L” and at that time angrily gave a tape to an intern for Jimmy; who in turn played it for Dre and the rest is history. Since then… Em has made it a POINT to not ever get beaten, and if you have beef with him… Em will taunt you on his tracks for as long as he lives. ✌️

What do you mean beaten? If you mean in a freestyle battle, then he lost to MC Juice in the 1997 scribble jam battles finale. With that being said, freestyle battles aren’t even close to being a measurement of one’s real rapping ability. It’s similar to a dunk contest in the nba. Lot of style but no real substance. Eminem is a prodigious writer and rap artist. As a real MC, Juice couldn’t hold a candle next to him. Eminem truly is a combination of prodigy poet, phenomenal vocalist, who grew up in the streets and latched on to hip hop as his outlet. People can deny all they want, but who can really write and rap on the same level as him? I can’t think of any

Yes. His discography doesn’t match up to the all time greats. When you think of “classic Eminem” albums (not just classic) he has two, the Slim Shady and Marshall Mathers LPs. They’ve aged horribly. They were good at the time but I guarantee you you won’t roll the windows down and blast it all the time for you and others to hear. And that’s likely because all that angst that led to murderous thoughts of an ex-wife, constant homophobia and other acts of pretty much teenaged belligerence don’t fly well today. And remember, I didn’t say tracks. I said albums. If you can’t listen to an entire album with cringing or skipping, it’s not a classic. And without classics, you’re beat. Skill and talent mean nothing of what you produce doesn’t stack up to it.

It depends on what you mean by “beaten”. If you mean in terms of a feud, then no. Those who’ve challenged Eminem tend to lose although some felt Machine Gun Kelly had a better diss than Eminem (I liked both). If you mean in terms of lyricism, there can be no doubt Eminem is one of the bests lyricists hip-hop has ever seen. However, there are lyricists such as Nas, Jay Z, Talib Kweli, and others who are arguably as good, if not better. Personally, I’ve never heard a rapper rap better than Nas did on his debut. In terms of commercial success, then no (Tupac I believe comes closest). However, to think that Eminem being white doesn’t help him with sales is to be delusional (even he admitted this).

This question is loaded . Rap beef (non physical/personal) is quite rare . The word 'Beaten' is subjective . Eminem has traditionally taken the position of the agressor in all of his "beefs" most of which don't include actual rappers . So with that , the answer is No. But the context would be that he's never went at any of his lyrical peers who are respected MC's . A list of his beefs include Benzino, Mariah Carey, Brittany Spears, Moby, His Mom , George Bush … mostly Celebrities . So no he's never lost . But he's never really won against an actual MC either.

Em came up in the battle rap circuit, so no doubt he’s got plenty of losses. No one goes undefeated forever. Theres a pretty well known battle he had at a Scribble Jam around 1997 where he battled Juice and lost. But the judging of rap battles is pretty fickle business, it’s rarely about lyricism. Thesaurus lost to a tiny Australian kid, because the crowd was feeling his energy more. Eyedea, who was a superb lyricist, lost to P.E.A.C.E., who just had more swagger. Dose One beat Eyedea, Sage Francis and others multiple times, the cards were just in his favor. Even Canibus, one of the most highly respected, legendary battlers worldwide, lost to Dizaster in Canada because he went in unprepared. He broke a cardinal rule for rhyming in what’s now known as ‘The Notebook Battle’.
